1
00:00:04,610 --> 00:00:07,620
Use of additional encodings is not

2
00:00:07,620 --> 00:00:11,300
the only way to include a third variable in a multivariate plot.

3
00:00:11,300 --> 00:00:16,649
One other way of adding an additional dimension to plots is through the use of faceting.

4
00:00:16,649 --> 00:00:20,234
When we facet univariate plots by levels of a second variable,

5
00:00:20,234 --> 00:00:22,009
we get a bivariate plot.

6
00:00:22,010 --> 00:00:25,470
When we facet bivariate plots by levels of a third variable,

7
00:00:25,469 --> 00:00:27,519
we get a multivariate plot.

8
00:00:27,519 --> 00:00:29,089
Earlier in this lesson,

9
00:00:29,089 --> 00:00:33,320
you saw the multivariate scatter plot of interest rates by loan amounts,

10
00:00:33,320 --> 00:00:37,399
with different borrower classes indicated by different point shapes.

11
00:00:37,399 --> 00:00:40,879
One alternative way that we could have displayed the data is by

12
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:44,225
faceting by the categorical variable like this.

13
00:00:44,225 --> 00:00:48,660
Separating each borrower class into its own subplot.

14
00:00:48,659 --> 00:00:52,729
We aren't limited to faceting by only one variable.

15
00:00:52,729 --> 00:00:56,114
We could also choose to facet plots across two variables,

16
00:00:56,115 --> 00:00:59,289
one on the rows, and one on the columns.

17
00:00:59,289 --> 00:01:02,179
If we had known period as another variable,

18
00:01:02,179 --> 00:01:06,439
then we could facet the data by rows in addition to the classes by columns.

